description:
This course will convey the basic concepts of occupational and environmental exposure science: the fundamental and practical aspects of assessing and controlling exposures to hazardous agents, broadly defined, encountered in occupational, residential, and ambient environments. The course is designed to provide the knowledge and skills necessary to assess exposure, and understand how upstream processes, including environmental justice and environmental racism, impact risks for health. 

Major topics include: recognition and evaluation of the various pathways and routes of exposure to chemical, physical, and biological hazards; air, water, soil, surface, food, and consumer product contamination; control hierarchies, strategies, and technologies, criteria, and standards; the international dimension; the regulatory landscape; prevention and sustainability (by design); environmental justice and environmental racism.

By the end of this course, you will be able to discuss and identify:     
- sources and transport of contaminants in occupational and ambient environmental settings, including exposures in marginalized and environmental justice communities;
- the conditions under which people or other living species could be exposed and how this differs across communities based on historical inequities;
- identification and quantification of exposure pathways;
- opportunities for mitigation or control of contaminants in both occupational and ambient environmental settings (including how these opportunities differ in historically marginalized settings);
- the design of exposure assessment strategies;
- integration of exposure and population information;
- the evaluation of historical (exposure reconstruction), current and prospective exposures and factors influencing these exposures (e.g., environmental racism).

This 3-credit online course examines the program development process with specific focus on planning and implementing health promotion programs. Health promotion programs are broadly defined, and include the following health promotion strategies: health communication, health education, policy advocacy, environmental change, health service provision, and community mobilization. By the end of the course, you will understand and apply key concepts related to developing a health promotion program.
Real world examples of health promotion programs can facilitate your learning and prepare you for your future careers. In this course, we will do this in two ways. First, I will link you to individuals directly involved with health promotion programs in Washtenaw County through their work at the Washtenaw County Health Department (WCHD). Through conversations (in real time and recorded) with these representatives, you will develop a program to address the needs of a Washtenaw County community. Budgetary, staffing, and timeframe details will be provided by the WCHD representatives in order to create programs of potential utility to the department. Alternatively, you are allowed to work with a health department or community organization of their choice (with my approval) to develop a health promotion program. Secondly, you will consider three case-studies of health programs via interviews with the program leaders. Both the interactions with the WCHD representative and health program case-studies will encourage learning through discussion boards and careful case analysis. 
While you are free to use and focus your time on any program planning approach you wish, we will focus on intervention mapping.  Group projects are strongly encouraged throughout this course.

After taking this course, you will be able to:
- Describe approaches to health promotion programs;
- Identify a health issue and priority population;
- Consider historical and structural factors that may impact the priority population and/or the health promotion program;
- Critically assess the relevant literature; 
- Develop a vision, SMART goals, and program objectives that address the health issue; 
- Create program activities and evaluation plans that link to goals and objectives; 
- Construct a program implementation timeline (i.e. Gantt Chart) and work plan;
- Calculate a budget and justify budgetary expenses; and
- Consider the needed membership for a multisector collaboration.

This third course in the “Good with Words: Writing and Editing” series will give you a number of strategies to help with what is often the most intimidating, even paralyzing part of the writing process: getting started.

You’ll learn about the “planning fallacy” and “temptation bundling.” You’ll get a chance to experiment with “freewriting” and “writing before you are ready.” And you’ll continue to benefit, through our ongoing “Good Sentences” and “Takeaways” segments, from the models and advice of a diverse set of writers. 

As with the other three courses in this series, you will also get access to a wide range of books and other resources you can use even after you finish the course. These include:

(1)the readings and exercises provided to the students who have taken the in-person version of this course at the University of Michigan and the University of Chicago;

(2)two digital libraries of excellent writing from a diverse collection of journalists, scientists, novelists, poets, historians, and entrepreneurs; 

(3)a monthly “Good Sentences” email.

This fourth and final course in the “Good with Words: Writing and Editing” series will help you master perhaps the most important step in the writing process: revising. You’ll learn about the difference between editing and proofreading. You’ll practice “un-numbing the numbers” so that data and statistics you use are clear and compelling. And you’ll be introduced to a framework for giving and receiving feedback that helpfully systematizes what should be cut and what should be kept from each draft.

As with the other three courses in this series, you will also get access to a wide range of books and other resources you can use even after you finish the course. These include:

(1)the readings and exercises provided to the students who have taken the in-person version of this course at the University of Michigan and the University of Chicago;

(2)two digital libraries of excellent writing from a diverse collection of journalists, scientists, novelists, poets, historians, and entrepreneurs; 

(3)a monthly “Good Sentences” email.

This second course in the Good with Words: Writing and Editing series will help you become an effective architect of information, both with your sentences and with your paragraphs. You’ll learn that the traditional advice to “Show, don’t tell” is incomplete and that skilled writers actually switch back and forth between showing and telling.

You’ll also learn more about the menu of time management techniques introduced in the first course of the series, including “deep work,” “studio time,” and “the Animal Farm Principle.” And as with the other three courses in this series, you will get access to a wide range of books and other resources you can use even after you finish the course. These include:

